\title{whittakerr: Whittaker Biome Classification and Mapping}
\description{
Tools for classifying locations into Whittaker biomes using
annual mean temperature and annual precipitation. Supports
point-based classification, Whittaker-diagram plotting,
geographic biome mapping at multiple resolutions, vector
smoothing of biome boundaries, and KML export for Google
Earth visualization.
}
\section{Conceptual basis}{


The package implements the verification machinery that was
structurally unavailable to Whittaker himself: applying his
classification to a global, queryable, fine-resolution climate
surface, and rendering the result both in T-P diagram space
and on the Earth's actual terrain. For the conceptual
development, see the accompanying Quarto document
(\code{kimbridges-documents.netlify.app/whittakerr/}).
}

\section{Unit convention}{


Precipitation is in centimeters throughout the public API.
This matches the underlying biome polygon data
(\code{\link{Whittaker_biomes}} carries a \code{precp_cm}
column) and the diagram's native unit. WorldClim returns
precipitation in millimeters; \code{\link{get_climate}}
provides both \code{map_mm} and \code{map_cm} in its output
tibble so callers can use whichever they need.

Exception: the project's cover-art image
(\code{whittakerr_cover_art_text.png} at the project root)
displays "mm" on its precipitation axis. This is intentional
project lore about the unit-naming history; the cover art
is not regenerated to match the cm convention.
}

\section{Key functions}{


Climate retrieval:
\itemize{
  \item \code{\link{get_climate}}: annual mean temperature
    and annual precipitation at one or more points, from
    WorldClim v2.1 (historical or CMIP6 future).
}

Biome classification:
\itemize{
  \item \code{\link{name_biome}}: classify one (T, P) pair.
  \item \code{\link{map_biomes}}: build a biome map for a
    region polygon at chosen resolution.
}

Diagram and map rendering:
\itemize{
  \item \code{\link{plot_biomes}}: render in T-P diagram
    space, with optional point and label overlays.
  \item \code{\link{smooth_biome_map}}: add smoothed boundary
    polygons to a biome_map.
  \item \code{\link{plot_biome_map}}: render in geographic
    space (grid or vector mode).
  \item \code{\link{export_biome_kml}}: write a KML file for
    Google Earth, with polygons clamped to terrain.
}
}

